Data Types in Python: Python is a dynamically typed language, which means you don‚Äôt need to declare data types explicitly‚ÄîPython infers them automatically.
‚úÖ Built-in Data Types (Core Categories):
Category                         	Data Types                    	Example
Numeric	                          int, float, complex	            10, 3.14, 2 + 3j
Text	                            str	                            "Hello", 'Python'
Boolean                         	bool	                           True, False
Sequence	                        list, tuple, range              [1,2,3], (1,2), range(5)
Set	                              set, frozenset	                 {1, 2, 3}
Mapping                         	dict                             {'name': 'Akancha'}
Binary	                          bytes, bytearray, memoryview	     b"abc"
None Type                        	NoneType                         	None

| Data Type      | Mutable | Ordered  | Example            |
| -------------- | ------- | -------- | ------------------ |
| `int`, `float` | ‚ùå       | ‚úÖ        | `10`, `3.14`       |
| `str`          | ‚ùå       | ‚úÖ        | `"hello"`          |
| `list`         | ‚úÖ       | ‚úÖ        | `[1, 2, 3]`        |
| `tuple`        | ‚ùå       | ‚úÖ        | `(1, 2, 3)`        |
| `set`          | ‚úÖ       | ‚ùå        | `{1, 2, 3}`        |
| `dict`         | ‚úÖ       | ‚úÖ (3.7+) | `{"key": "value"}` |

Type casting in python:
Typecasting (or type conversion) is the process of converting one data type into another.
1. Implicit Typecasting (Automatic): Python automatically converts data types when needed.
a = 5         # int
b = 2.0       # float
c = a + b     # a is implicitly converted to float
print(c)      # 7.0
print(type(c))  # <class 'float'>

2. Explicit Typecasting (Manual): You manually convert one data type into another using functions like:
| Function  | Converts to    |
| --------- | -------------- |
| `int()`   | Integer        |
| `float()` | Floating-point |
| `str()`   | String         |
| `bool()`  | Boolean        |
| `list()`  | List           |
| `tuple()` | Tuple          |
| `set()`   | Set            |

